Introduction

Air is an essential element in out living planet breathe. However, with the development of industry around the world, air pollution gradually risen public awarness. There are plenty of countries around the world are affected by air pollution. According to the WHO report, there are 3.8 million premature deaths annually are attributed to outdoor air pollution. About 80% of those deaths are due to heart disease and stroke, 20% are from respiratory illnesses and cancers related to exposure to fine particulate matter (PM2.5), the most health-harmful air pollutant. In this project, we studies the air pollutant PM2.5 in Seoul,South Korean. Seoul Metropolitan Government provide the daily report from the Jongno-gu station in 2019. We use 2019 whole year dataset as the train data in this project and we make some prediction about the future Seoul air pollutant PM2.5. We hope base on our analysis, the forecast of the future air pollutant PM2.5 can arise more people attention and responsible for maintaining a safe environment.

Analysis

The plot of 2019 Air pollutant PM2.5 data in Jongno-gu station.

data <- read.csv("/Users/apple/Desktop/data1year.csv",header=TRUE)
pollution = as.ts(data$PM2.5)
plot(pollution, main = "2019 Air pollutant PM2.5", xlab = "Day",ylab = "PM2.5")

Base on the plot of the air pollate PM2.5, we can find there are no obvious trend and seasonal effect in the plot, but we can find there are some cyclical effects and a large cyclical effects appears around 200.

acf(pollution)

Base on the acf plot of the air polluate PM2.5, we can find the acf value is decreasing(some of large value at lag 9 and lag 12), and the acf plot shows it is non-statinary time series, it is time dependent.

  1. Firstly, We try to use differncing to smooth our time series.
pollution_diff = diff(pollution)
plot(pollution_diff)

acf(pollution_diff)

pacf(pollution_diff)

Base on the acf plot shows, after the series of first differnce appear stationary. The acf is random and small for lag>0.

Model fitting

  1. Base on the acf and pacf plot, we try the first model ARMA(2,6)
M1 = arima(pollution_diff,order = c(6,0,2), include.mean = FALSE)
tsdiag(M1)

AIC(M1)
## [1] 3045.438

The model fit well in terms of model diagnostics and have the lowest AIC values. Base on the term of model diagnostics, the plot shows all the p-value is larger in the Box- Ljung tests, above the sigiificant level 0.05, we are not reject the null hypothesis, so it is a good model fit. In term of AIC, we find the AIC value is equal to 3045.438. The AIC value kind large.

M2 = arima(pollution_diff,order = c(6,0,1), include.mean = FALSE)
tsdiag(M2)

AIC(M2)
## [1] 3044.868

Base on the term of model diagnostics, the plot shows all the p-value is larger in the Box- Ljung tests, above the sigiificant level 0.05, we are not reject the null hypothesis, so it is a good model fit. In term of AIC, we find the AIC value is equal to 3044.868. The AIC value kind smaller than M1. So, M2 is slight better than M1.

M3 = arima(pollution_diff,order = c(0,0,3),include.mean = FALSE)
tsdiag(M3)

AIC(M3)
## [1] 3040.788

Base on the term of model diagnostics, the plot shows all the p-value is larger in the Box- Ljung tests, above the sigiificant level 0.05, we are not reject the null hypothesis, so it is a good model fit. In term of AIC, we find the AIC value is equal to 3040.778. The AIC value kind smaller than M2,however,base on the Ljung-Box statistic plot, we can see there are smaller p value appere between the lag 8 and lag 10. Even some models have low AIC values, but the fitness in terms of model diagnostic are not as good as above.

Forcast & Prediction

Using the differences in December 2019 PM2.5 pollutate value as the test ser for the models and the remaining data as the train set, compare the models in abouve we choose.

train =1:(length(pollution_diff)-30)
trainx = pollution_diff[train]
testx = pollution_diff[-train]
model = arima (trainx, order = c(2,0,7))
foremodel = predict (model, 30)
err = sum ((testx - foremodel$pred)^2)
print(err)
## [1] 20174.64

Base on the caculation above we find the sum of prediction error is 20174.76 over the test set.

Conclusion

Air is an essential element in our living planet. However, with the development of industry around the world, air pollution gradually raised public awareness.There are plenty of countries around the world that are affected by air pollution. According to the WHO report [2], 3.8 million premature deaths annually are attributed to outdoor air pollution. About 80% of those deaths are due to heart disease and stroke, 20% are from respiratory illnesses and cancers related to exposure to fine particulate matter (PM2.5), the most health-harmful air pollutant. Based on our model prediction, we expect the air pollutant PM2.5 will be higher in the future. We hope based on our analysis, the forecast of the future air pollutant PM2.5 can raise more peoples attention and be responsible for maintaining a safe environment. Referece: Air pollution.
